observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Require the MA to prepare a detailed schedule and aging of Guaranty Deposit Payable account under the General Fund (GF), Special Education Fund (SEF) and Trust Fund (TF);

Cause the release of the retention money to its suppliers/contractors in accordance with the provision of COA Circular No. 2012-001.

We recommended that Management:

Implement uniformly the salary step increment in accordance with the provisions of CSC-DBM JC No. 1 s. 2012 and No. 1 s. of 2016 so that employees will not be discouraged in performing their duties and responsibilities;

In view of the current financial constraints, grant the most beneficial to the employees in accordance with the applicable rules and regulations on the granting of benefits and;

Give attention on the salary progress status of the Municipal employees based on meritorious performance as soon as the LGU had the capacity to grant benefits, so that proper recognition may be given to those deserving workers who were stuck in their position for a very long time.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Establish a Disposal Committee to oversee and facilitate the proper disposal of unserviceable properties of the MGI;
Direct the MGSO to securely store unserviceable properties to prevent further deterioration;
Require the Municipal Accountant to assist the MGSO in preparing the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) by providing the necessary information; and
Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 in order to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Engineer and other concerned project implementers to conduct an immediate validation and documentation of the actual physical completion of all projects recorded under the CIP account, particularly the ₱16,139,781.51 balance, to confirm their status and readiness for reclassification;
Facilitate legal consultation or initiate coordination with the heirs or authorized legal representatives of the deceased contractor to establish any legitimate claims or secure formal waivers, which are necessary to resolve pending obligations and enable the proper closure of accounts;
Ensure the prompt issuance of Certificates of Completion and Acceptance Reports for infrastructure projects that have been completed, as these documents are essential for recognizing the asset in the government books and for commencing depreciation in accordance with applicable accounting standards; and
Require the Municipal Accountant, upon full settlement of project obligations, to reclassify the CIP balance to the appropriate PPE account, and to recognize the corresponding depreciation expense effective the year the asset was completed and placed in service, not the year of payment.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to conduct an inspection and prepare a report for completed projects that have not yet been paid for;
Prepare a formal letter to unpaid contractors requesting submission of supporting documents (SDs) to substantiate their claims against the Municipality;
Instruct the MAO to investigate and reconcile the accumulated amount of ₱411,747.86, consisting of interest income and taxes withheld from various trust funds, which remains unresolved due to insufficient historical documentation, to ensure proper classification and transparency in financial reporting; and
Expedite the closure of pending projects to enable the utilization of the ₱411,318.18 DAR incentive fund, thereby maximizing its intended developmental benefits; and
Strategically plan and continue efforts to implement PPAs funded by various NGAs within the agreed timeframe to ensure timely delivery of benefits to constituents and optimize the use of funds;

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the accurate and complete filling out of DTT for every travel to ensure accurate recording and monitoring of trips, vehicle mileage, and driver activities;
Compel the submission of Monthly Report of Official Travels and Monthly Reports of Fuel Consumptions to the AT to ensure transparency, accountability, and compliance with auditing requirements;
Instruct the drivers to indicate the odometer reading in the DTT, and if odometer is out of order, require the Municipal General Services Office to request for its immediate repair or replacement in order to determine the actual fuel consumption; and
Set guidelines on the limitation of fuel consumption considering the vehicle type, distance, and other relevant factors to promote responsible fuel management, prevent excessive fuel usage, and ensure that fuel consumption is reasonable and justifiable.

We commended the MAO for their exemplary efforts in ensuring full compliance with the withholding and remittance requirements for obligations due to the BIR, GSIS, and PhilHealth. Their consistent adherence to regulatory deadlines and proper remittance procedures reflects a strong commitment to sound financial governance. We recommended and the Management agreed to continue implementation and strengthening of these established practices.
Regarding the unpaid HDMF remittance, we respectfully recommended and the LCE agreed to take the following actions:
Direct the MAO to retrieve all payroll records covering the period when HDMF contribution deductions for JO personnel were first implemented;
Instruct the MAO to update the necessary records and coordinate with the HDMF for guidance on how to properly handle amounts withheld prior to the registration of affected JO personnel;
Require MHRMO to ensure that all newly hired JO personnel submit their HDMF membership numbers prior to the processing of their wages;
Mandate the MHRMO to assist all unregistered JO personnel in completing their HDMF membership registration, in compliance with HDMF regulations; and
Direct the MAO and MHRMO to ensure on-going compliance with all laws, rules, and regulations concerning the deduction and remittance of HDMF contributions, including maintaining up-to-date documentation and proper coordination with concerned agencies.

We recommended that the LCE to take the following actions:

Direct the Municipal Engineer (ME) to prepare an inspection report on completed projects that remain unpaid;

Draft a formal letter to unpaid contractors regarding their claims with the Municipality, requesting submission of necessary documents to substantiate their claims;

Strategically plan the implementation phase of unimplemented PPAs to optimize the use of funds received from SAs within the agreed timeframe; and

Continue the efforts exerted in the implementation of PPAs funded by various NGAs to ensure timely delivery of intended benefits to constituents.

We recommended that Management:

Prioritize efforts to address the deficiencies identified by the Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR) and work towards fulfilling the prescribed requirements for the SWMP.  This may involve revising and enhancing the existing plan to align with regulatory standards and submitting it for approval promptly;

Immediately improve the poor operation of the controlled dumpsite, and;

Implement the "No Segregation, No Collection" policy to encourage residents and businesses to participate actively in waste segregation efforts.

We recommended that the LCE:

Direct the MAO to retrieve all payroll records dating back to the initiation of HDMF contributions deductions;

Update the records and seek guidance from HDMF on the appropriate action regarding the withheld amounts prior to JO Personnel Registration;

Instruct new JO personnel to provide their respective HDMF numbers to the MGI to ensure timely remittance of any deductions from their salary;

Direct the Municipal Human Resource Management Officer to assist the JO workers without HDMF numbers to secure the same, in compliance with HDMF regulations on remittance of deductions; and

Ensure continuous compliance with existing laws, rules, and regulations governing deductions and remittance of HDMF contributions.

We recommended that Management:

Follow up incessantly the requested documents from the contractors and ensure their completeness and authenticity before facilitating final payments;

Prepare and send letter to the contractors if they are still willing to collect the unpaid amount;

Plan meticulously the implementation phase of the unimplemented PPAs to optimally utilize the funds received from the Source Agencies (SA) within the agreed timeframe; and

Continue the efforts exerted in the implementation of PPAs funded by various NGAs to deliver the intended benefits on time to constituents.

We recommended that the LCE:

Require the MT and/or Supply Officer and the MA to maintain properly and update the stock cards and Supplies Ledger Cards, respectively, and to reconcile their records regularly;

Facilitate the completion of delayed infrastructure projects through constant monitoring and coordination with concerned personnel/departments/agency;

Submit the distribution list of 10 units of 4 in 1 HP Diesel Engine Water Pump with accessories; and

Comply strictly with GPPB Resolution No. 20-2020 and Occupational Safety and Health Standards in the implementation of infrastructure projects by administration.

Prepare a three-year program indicating strategic prioritization policies in the allocation of the SEF to schools;

Gather and keep records of the information needed to be considered in the planning and budgeting for SEF;

Consolidate the project proposals prepared and submitted by the School Heads for their respective SEF allocation which shall form part of the documentary support for the approval of the SEF Budget;

Submit to the Audit Team the schools’ SOB, APP and PPMP along with the approved SEF Budget and the approved projects proposals of the schools allocated with the fund for verification; and

Observe the policies in the planning and budgeting for SEF and the procedures and timelines in the preparation and approval of the budget for the said fund as stated in the DepEd, DBM and DILG JC No. 01, series of 2017.

We recommended and Management agreed to require the:
MAO and the MGSO or Municipal Treasurer (MT) to prepare and submit the necessary reports and records pertaining to local road network in accordance with the prescribed formats as provided under COA Circular No. 2015-008;
MA and the GSO/MT to conduct regular reconciliation of LRNLCs and the LRNPCs at least on quarterly basis;
ME to furnish the MA and the GSO/MT with complete descriptions and cost segregations of various road components of completed road projects as basis for recording in their respective records; and
MA to disclose the total road network in the Notes to the FS as per Annex B of the aforesaid circular.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Instruct the MA to account properly the acquisition and issuance of construction materials based on IPSAS 12 - Inventories, and make the necessary book adjustments to reflect the correct balances of the affected Inventory and CIP accounts;
Require the MT and/or Supply Officer and the MA to maintain properly and update the stock cards and SLCs, respectively, and to reconcile their records regularly;
Procure tools and construction equipment otherwise stop the implementation of project by administration as required by item 3.2 (b) of GPPB Resolution No. 20-2020;
Stop the practice of advance payment for rental of tools and construction equipment;
Require the MHRMO to issue uniform policy guidelines on hiring of JO personnel to strengthen internal controls pertaining thereto;
Facilitate the completion of delayed infrastructure projects through constant monitoring and coordination with concerned personnel/departments/agency;
Correct the deficiencies observed on the projects Improvement of Tourism Facilities - Irosin Lake and Rehabilitation of Line Canal at Purok 4 of Barangay San Juan;
Submit the distribution list of 10 units of 4 in 1 HP Diesel Engine Water Pump with accessories; and
Comply strictly with GPPB Resolution No. 20-2020 and OSHS in the implementation of infrastructure projects by administration.

We recommended and Management agreed to direct the MA to:
Conduct periodic reconciliation of the LDRRMF balance based on the Report on the Sources and Utilization of LDRRMF with the related Cash in Bank balance;
Maintain separate SL for LDRRMF MF MOOE and CO;
Prepare and submit to the AT the Notes to FS for LDRRMF with complete details/information and in the correct format; and
Transfer the unutilized LDRRMF-QRF and MF-MOOE as of December 31, 2021 to the STF.
We also recommended and Management directed the MBO to:
Maintain separate RAAO for LDRRMF MF-MOOE and MF-CO;
Coordinate with the MA for setting up of RAAO for prior year unexpended LDRRMF transferred to STF; and
Prepare and submit to the AT the revised SAAOB for the LDRRMF as of December 31, 2021 with the corrected amounts of fund utilization.
We also recommended and Management required the MA and the MBO to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records to ensure that the amounts reported for the appropriation and utilization of the LDRRMF are correct.

Likewise, we recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the concerned departments to determine if PPAs that remained unimplemented as of December 31, 2021 can be reprogrammed or reallocated instead to other priority PPAs;
Monitor closely the implementation of all PPAs under the 20% DF to ensure prompt completion and to facilitate the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund, if needed, to other prioritized PPAs to maximize the utilization thereof;
Conduct reconciliation of records between the MBO, MAO and the MPDO to provide accurate 20% DF Utilization Report.

We recommended that Management:

Require the concerned personnel or office to collate the pertinent documents relative to the hanging CIP accounts and process the unpaid portion of the project cost;

Determine the appropriate action against the contractor if the latter has still deficiencies or documents needed to be submitted relative to their contract with the Municipality; 

Require the MEO and the MA Office concerned personnel to properly coordinate with each other especially during the last quarter of the CY in order to have harmonious records relative to the CIP accounts of the LGU; and

Require the concerned implementing office to immediately process the papers or documents relative to the payment of materials or labor costs of the projects implemented thru administration, if the project was determined to be 100 per cent physically completed to avoid the accumulation of the same in the CIP accounts.

Exert extra effort and obtain all the necessary documents needed to support the identified reconciling items and draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to record all valid reconciling items that require adjustment/correction in the book; 

Cause the cancellation of stale checks with available records and prepare the necessary adjusting entries so that the Cash in Bank, LCCA and the corresponding Payable and Equity accounts balance will be fairly presented in the financial statements;

Transfer the amount of ₱21,691.52 that represent the bank error to bank account SA 2602-1026-72 (GF-PGMA) from SA Account number 2602-1049-26 (GF-Restricted Fund); and 

Ensure that any errors committed by the bank which were identified during the preparation of the BRS be immediately communicated to the concerned depository bank.

Continue the good practice in monitoring the cash advances granted to the municipal officials and employees;

Issue demand letters compelling the officials or employees to immediately settle in full their outstanding cash advances, either by liquidation, by payment/refund or through salary deductions, whichever is applicable; and

Strictly comply with the requirements of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular Nos. 97-002 and 2012-001 and all other related rules and regulations pertaining to the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

Adopt the Perpetual Inventory Method in the recording and issuance of supplies and materials and comply with the process and documentation prescribed under Sections 114 and 121 of the NGAS Manual;

Prepare the SSMI that shall be used as a basis in preparing the JEV to record the supplies and materials issued;

Submit the list of beneficiaries for the project “Provision of Toilet Construction Materials to Household in Schistosomiasis-Endemic Barangays” duly received/signed to the Auditor for verification; and

Hire or designate a GSO or Supply Officer who will be in-charge or take custody of and be accountable for all properties owned by the LGU.

Make a representation or confirm from the SAs as to whether or not the balance of the funds transferred to the Municipality with completed PPAs should be returned or be utilized by the LGU;

Determine the PPAs to be appropriated with the fund transfers received by the Municipality as awards in accordance with the pertinent  guidelines issued by the agencies that give the same;

Require the Municipal Accountant to exert effort to properly identify the sources and status of implementation of the related PPAs for the funds transferred by NGAs and prepare a comprehensive schedule for the same; and

Return the said unutilized funds to the Bureau of National Treasury, if the documents or records of the specific accounts could no longer be located or traced.

Provide legal basis for the method of distribution of SET proceeds which pertains to CY 1991 and prior, otherwise, follow the provisions of the LGC of 1991;

Require the Municipal Treasurer/Municipal Accountant to confirm with the Provincial Government as to the balance of unremitted SET of the Municipality as of December 31, 2020; and

Remit or utilize the subject amount of the Due to LGUs account.

Require the Municipal Accountant to exert effort to properly identify the sources and status of implementation of the funds transferred by other LGUs particularly in the TF book;

Make a representation or confirm from the SAs as to whether the balance of the funds transferred to the Municipality should be returned or be utilized by the LGU;

Make the corresponding correcting entry to properly close the WHSMP - LGU Counterpart of the LGU;  and

If the documents or records of the specific accounts cannot be located or trace anymore, request the said accounts for write-off.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit the revised details of LDRRMF as presented in the CY 2019 Notes to FS taking into consideration the changes in the unutilized amounts of the QRF and MF for the said year;

Direct the MBO to prepare and submit the revised SAAOB for the LDRRMF as of December 31, 2020 taking into consideration the variances noted in the reported amounts of the appropriation and utilization of the CY 2020 LDRRMF;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to transfer the amount of the unutilized financial assistance received by the Municipality from other LGUs and other source agencies to the General Fund; and

Ensure compliance with the provisions of the COA Circular No. 2012-002 particularly in the recording and reporting for the LDRRMF.

Exercise prudence in recommending approval for the grant of leave monetization;

Ensure that officials and employees availing of monetization of vacation leave credits has accumulated no less than 15 days, in which case he can monetize no more than ten days and that five days of VL credits will remain after monetization which shall be availed only once a year;

Avoid approving monetization of more than 30 days leave credits unless for valid and justifiable reasons;

Submit to COA at the beginning of the year, the list of all on-going government PPAs and those that are to be implemented during the year;

Inform the Audit Team within 10 days after the award of the infrastructure project or before it commence, that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted; 

Ensure the monthly preparation and submission of the monitoring report on PPAs to the Office of the Auditor; and

Include in the report all the PPAs implemented by the LGU regardless of its amount or source of funds and whether the said PPAs were implemented by contract or otherwise.

Implement uniformly the implementation of salary step increment in accordance with the provisions of CSC-DBM JC No. 1 s. 2012 and No. 1 s. of 2016 so that employees will not be discouraged in performing their duties and responsibilities;

In view of the current financial constraints, grant the most beneficial to the employees in accordance with the applicable rules and regulations on the granting of benefits and;

Give attention on the salary progress status of the Municipal employees based on meritorious performance as soon as the LGU had the capacity to grant benefits, so that proper recognition may be given to those deserving workers who were stuck in their position for a very long time.

Remit immediately the long-outstanding balances and ensure timely remittance of the monthly dues to avoid the imposition of penalties, surcharges and interest arising from delayed remittances;

Enjoin the concerned personnel to update their accounts and fully settle their overdue or matured loans with the GSIS; and



Exhaust all means to pay the obligations of their officials and employees who will be separated from the service, such as utilizing their Terminal Leave Benefits to avoid further accumulation of interests and penalties.

Make a representation with the Land Registration Authority to confirm the ownership of all land properties and thereafter, secure copies of the Torrens Title or any equivalent document relative thereto;

Ensure proper safekeeping of the newly secured and subsequently acquired Land Titles; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to record the properties over which the Municipality has acquired absolute ownership.

