We recommended that Management strictly adhere to Sections 22 and 23 of the amendment to Rule XVI of the Omnibus Rules Implementing Book V of EO No. 292 per CSC MC No. 41, s. 1998 and CSC MC No. 16 s. 2002 on the guidelines on Monetization of Leave Credits.

We also recommended that the Municipal Human Resource Management Officer (HRMO):

Exercise prudence in recommending approval for the grant of leave monetization;



Ensure that officials and employees availing of monetization of vacation leave credits has accumulated no less than 15 days, in which case he can monetize no more than ten days and that five days of VL credits will remain after monetization which shall be availed only once a year;

Avoid approving monetization of more than 30 days leave credits unless for valid and justifiable reasons;

Strictly follow the conditions prescribed in Section 23 of the Omnibus Rules on Leave in case officials and employees chose to avail the special monetization; and

Stop allowing the practice of monetizing sick leave or combination of vacation and sick leave credit balances.



Further, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant check the validity and completeness of the supporting documents before processing any payments for leave monetization.

We recommended that Management:

Submit to the Audit Team the documents related with the contract time extension as stated in the report on the Government Programs, Projects, and Activities  (GPPAs);

Evaluate the performance of the contractor in order to determine if they are at fault so that liquidated damages may be imposed in accordance with the pertinent provisions of RA No. 9184;

Observe proper timing of implementation of the infrastructure projects especially if they are funded out of loan, to ensure that the Municipality can immediately benefit after the said projects are completed; 

Strictly follow the requirements of the 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of RA No. 9184 particularly those stated in Section 17.6 or the detailed engineering for the procurement of infrastructure projects; and 

Instruct the Municipal Engineer, the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) and the responsible focal person/offices to have coordinated conceptualization and stewardship for future development projects of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management:

Re-visit the status of the potable water system projects in the Barangays of Salvacion, Casini and Buenavista and institute appropriate actions to optimally utilized the implementation of the said projects;

Coordinate with the Barangay Officials on the maintenance and protection of the projects implemented in its respective barangays;

Refrain from pursuing a project in the absence of adequate study and due-diligence analysis concerning the undertaking; and


Instruct the Municipal Engineer and the MPDC and responsible focal person/offices to ensure coordinated conceptualization and stewardship for future development projects of the Municipality.

